div.div:
More direct methods can just apply one interface such as information rather than applying derivation methods or general differences to create similarities.
A graph where these variables/similarities are always positioned or adjacently positioned to make these queries trivial would be a generally useful graph, like a graph where the useful sequences of these similarities are always arranged in those sequences.
However, some queries like iteration/abstract queries will involve differences that will make different graph positioning functions useful, so a 'generally useful graph to make all solution automation workflows trivial' is non-trivial and more useful.
The above graph represents one workflow (like 'standardize, abstract, specify').
Another workflow would connect different bases/standards/similarities, such as 'connect problems to cross solutions on the way to problems' or 'connect solutions to find variables of solutions'.

div.div:
A workflow-info network (using variables as info) can make it clear what types of info can be connected by which workflows (info like randomness in some direction, or variability in the other).
For example, some workflow may be very general like 'try every possible solution (trial and error)' in which case it can solve any problem in which the solution can be identified, so it can connect all identifiable information (above some measurability threshold), but the workflow itself contains low information - if the solution metrics aren't well-defined, 'trial and error' won't help filter the solution space to reduce the set of solutions to try, and with some problems, 'trial and error' will still be testing solutions without having found any, when the solution is no longer useful or a more relevant solution-finding method has found a solution, so it can't always be useful in connecting info. Connecting very independent variables (like abstract concepts like relevance and abstraction) in every possible way is an example of a problem where trial and error won't really help, bc the info of the solution metrics requires understanding (iterating through every possible concept connection/combination to connect these two concepts could mean iterating through 1000-variable combinations, given the independence of these variables and if the variables being combined are less independent, requiring more of them to create an independent variable connection).
Nevertheless, 'trial and error' can still solve most problems, so it should always be a possible connection between any two nodes in a network of useful variables to connect, such as independent variables like interface variables.
Similarly, some workflows will use a concept connection in the workflow, so they will more trivially connect those concepts (in a way that can create other connections, to implement the workflow), such as how a 'cluster network of concept spectrums like variation/difference/abstraction/independence vs. constants/similarity/specificity/dependence' enables various workflows such as 'identify a set of optimal variation/constant connections or interim points of the cluster network and move the problem point or the problem/solution connection toward these optimal points/connections' or 'alternate between the difference and the similarity cluster (like filter/generate) to identify useful differences/similarities to apply'. So these workflows would connect 'variation/constant' or 'similarity/difference' on a concept network. (The workflow specifies a connection between these concepts in its definition).
Similarly, some workflows are better at identifying some info than others, in a way that is undefined/unrequired/surprising given the workflow's definition. A workflow that applies 'filters' is better at identifying 'specific' information, for example, 'specification' being related to filters, but not required to be relevant, since filters can be used to identify abstractions (identifying specific abstractions in that case) and filters can also be general like 'find a generally similar structure' and filters can also apply trivial specification, where some other interface variable is far more relevant than specificity.
